<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
It restricts content because you are forcing guilds to pass when they don't want to just because other guilds were pushing hard to get inserted into the rotation or the mob popped at an odd time. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I apologize if I think that getting into a rotation should be a *mite* harder than waltzing into a zone because you know the guild up for a mob won't be bothering with it until the 11th hour. <br>
<br>
Even when we got on the dozekar rotation, we started under the impression that we had to get there before Noble Blade, even though that wasn't the case after I talked to them. When we tried for Sev, we had plans to all be online right after the server up to the best of our ability. <br>
<br>
And since mobs can pop at odd times for *everyone* it's hardly unfair to specific groups. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
The idea that guilds have &quot;bigger fish to fry&quot; and are being lazy about killing sev is crap, because that is the entire reason they have 24 hours. They don't have to race to the mob, that's the reason for the rotation in the first place.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
The reason for the rotation is so that they don't have to race OTHER guilds who are on the rotation. If you had two guilds, one on rotation, and one off, you're damn right they'd have to race. You cannot claim that my &quot;bigger fish to fry&quot; statement is crap and then say...<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
and large guilds that have more important mobs that won't mobilize within a few hours after spawn<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
because the two positions are contradictions. You either admit that big guilds won't mobilize quickly on Sev, thus allowing opportunity for the rotation to stall, because, as you said yourself,<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
(and its about at the point where any 2-group 60+ set of people that are decently equipped can take him out no problem), <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Thus any guild or 12ish people who put a few weeks in HoT getting armor, and tracking down some good weapons can get on the rotation in front of a large guild who, as you've said, and I've said, have bigger fish to fry. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
The &quot;race&quot; of a guild not on a rotation to try and kill something before the guild up for it gets to it is a non-issue. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I have to restrain myself from flaming you here, and bear in mind that I am trying to keep this conversation in the general forum, but you have obviously misunderstood somehow, the entire issue. <br>
<br>
The *only* two ways that a guild can get on any rotation, is to either race and beat the guild up for the mob, or get the guild's permission. It is *not* a non-issue, as obviously a guild, as you said, relatively small, can mobilize up before a big guild that is doing other things. Thus, the larger guilds create a situation in which everyone after them, big guild and little guild alike, are pushed back by weeks, as other guilds slip into the rotation ahead of them. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
These proposals are nothing more than veiled attempts to limit content and limit the amount of time certain guilds have to wait between hitting Sev. <br>
It is about sharing, and the selfishness of some when it comes to sharing.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Listen, whatever interest you have in throwing out the 'selfishness and sharing' crap is fine, but if you would stop with the dogma for a minute, you'd understand that what we're trying to do is...<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
 have a rotation the way it is which is fair to EVERYONE because all have a chance to get on the rotation, and every guild gets the same amount of chances at sev per unit time,<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
yeah. You hold up the rotation for at most 2 spawn cycles of unit time, and then it moves on. That's a whole lot MORE fair than letting it stagnate at one point until someone has to come to the RTA's and post about it not being killed in a timely fashion. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
or put it off rotation. It boils down to nothing more than what was discussed on the thread about removing sev from rotation:<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I don't think you'll recall, purposely, but I was one of the ones that said &quot;don't take it off rotation, or the medium guilds will OWN it every time it pops&quot;. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Medium to medium-high guilds trying to get greater access to sev.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Right... because my members are on 24/7 whereas everyone else's members are offline for 16 hours a day. Do you not understand that I am proposing a bed that my guild would have to lay in as well? <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> <br>
In this case its just veiled in the bullshit story of &quot;keeping the rotation moving&quot;, <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Ok, I'll tell you what. You wait 2, 3 more months, tops, before the rotation for sev gets SO big, that people just say 'fuck it&quot; and go FFA on it. And then I say &quot;well, if people had been moving through the rotation at any kind of speed, maybe there would still BE a rotation&quot;. It's not QUITE as big as the list for Ragefire was, but it's getting there. What, 20 guilds at least now? More? <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
so that small guilds that can't mobilize within a few hours can be forced to pass due to other guilds getting prepared and taking him out quickly after spawn (and its about at the point where any 2-group 60+ set of people that are decently equipped can take him out no problem), <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
A small guild of... what? 11 people? 10? Remember, at less than 10, the server deletes your guild. If 12 people is not a small guild, I don't know what is. And if 12 can kill him, 12 can kill him. I know for a FACT that 6 people can farm HoT armor, because I've been in that group. 12 would be a cakewalk. <br>
<br>
So there's your &quot;small guilds won't be able to kill it&quot; argument down. Small guilds wouldn't be able to kill it without some forethought maybe, maybe the FFA sev they couldn't kill, but a planned sev, where they could plan to be there in advance, yeah, they'd kill that. Which is why I'm trying to find a solution to an oversized rotation that is getting increasingly long a wait, with no regulation and little forward movement. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
and large guilds that have more important mobs that won't mobilize within a few hours after spawn can be forced to passdue to other guilds getting prepared and taking him out quickly after spawn.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
If the large guild can't spare the time to port 2 groups into EJ, or even 3 groups (most large guilds I know have three porting members) and gank the 'easiest mob on rotation', then they must be REALLY doing something big... and if they are REALLY doing something big... then they should remove themselves from the sev rotation.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
The rotation is moving<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
